 <p>We restate a few equivalences and definitions from <xref ref="connectives"/> for easy reference.</p>

<assemblage>
<title>Logical Equivalences for Conditionals</title><idx><h>conditional</h><h>logical equvalences for</h></idx>
<p>
<ul>
  <li><m>p\rightarrow q\equiv \neg p\ \vee q</m></li>
  <li><m>\neg(p\rightarrow q)\equiv p\ \wedge \neg q</m></li>
</ul></p>

<p>Negating a universal conditional statement:
 <md><mrow>\neg(\forall x\in D, P(x)\rightarrow Q(x))&amp;\equiv \exists x\in D, \neg(P(x)\rightarrow Q(x))</mrow>
  <mrow>  &amp;\equiv \exists x\in D, P(x)\wedge \neg Q(x)</mrow>
</md></p>
  </assemblage>

<definition><statement><p>A conditional statement <m>p\rightarrow q</m> has
  <ul>
    <li><term>contrapositive</term><idx>contrapositive</idx>: <m>\neg q\rightarrow \neg p</m>;</li>
    <li><term>converse</term><idx>converse</idx>: <m>q\rightarrow p</m>;</li>
    <li><term>inverse</term><idx>inverse</idx>: <m>\neg p\rightarrow \neg q</m>.</li>
  </ul>
</p></statement>
</definition>

<p>We can extend the definition of contrapositive and converse to universal conditional statements.</p>

<definition xml:id="D_contrapositiveunivcond"><statement>
  <p>The universal conditional statement <m>\forall x\in D, P(x)\rightarrow Q(x)</m> has <term>contrapositive</term><idx><h>contrapositive</h><h>universal conditional</h></idx> <m>\forall x\in D, \neg Q(x)\rightarrow \neg P(x)</m>.</p></statement></definition>

<definition xml:id="D_converseunivcond"><statement>
  <p>The universal conditional statement <m>\forall x\in D, P(x)\rightarrow Q(x)</m> has <term>converse</term><idx><h>converse</h><h>universal conditional</h></idx> <m>\forall x\in D, Q(x)\rightarrow P(x)</m>.</p></statement></definition>

